XV. Α. Tun Summum Psms, in his Phrygian cap and goatskin chlamys, holding out the golden apple of Discord. This graceful specimen of the Roman school so exactly expresses the mingled effeminacy and heroism mark- ing the character of the Trojan youth, that its author may with reason be supposed to have drawn his inspiration from that masterpiece of early Greek sculpture thus graphically pictured to us by Pliny (xxxiv. 19, 16). “ Euphra- noris Alexander Paris est, in quo laudatur quod omnia simul intelligantur, judex Dearum, amator Helenae, et tamen Achillis interfector.” Sard. XV. a. Rouana, Mas-rna or 'rus Pammuu. The hero, having taken down the statuette of Pallas from its elevated pedestal. is seen in the act of descending from the altar, upon which he had climbed for that purpose. His companion‚ Ulysses, vanishes beyond the altar, keeping watch in the far dis- tance, which accounts for the disproportionate diminution of his figure. The nude statue of Venus indicates the scene of the exploit‚ the acropolis of Troy3 the moon and star overhead, the time, midnight3 the palm-branch at Diomede’s side the successful termination of the adventure.
